'''Metrolink''' is a [[commuter rail]] system in [[Southern California]], United States. Established in 1991 as the '''Southern California Regional Rail Authority''' ('''SCRRA'''), it began service the following year. 

The rail system operates lines in [[Ventura County, California|Ventura County]], [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]], [[San Bernardino County, California|San Bernardino County]], [[Riverside County, California|Riverside County]], [[Orange County, California|Orange County]], and [[San Diego County, California|San Diego County]].<ref name=RouteMap>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinktrains.com/documents/Stations/MetrolinkMap.pdf |title=Metrolink Routes |date=15 February 2010 |publisher=Metrolink |accessdate=28 March 2010}}</ref> It connects with the [[Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority|Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority's]] [[Los Angeles County Metro Rail|Metro Rail]] lines at [[Union Station (Los Angeles)|Union Station]] in [[Downtown Los Angeles]], and with the San Diego [[San Diego Coaster|Coaster]] and [[Sprinter (San Diego)|Sprinter]] lines at [[Oceanside, California|Oceanside]]. It also connects with [[Amtrak]]'s [[Pacific Surfliner]], [[Coast Starlight]], [[Southwest Chief]], and [[Sunset Limited]] trains.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amtrakcalifornia.com/rail/go/amtrak/stations/l_p/los-angeles/index.cfm |title=Los Angeles |publisher=Amtrak California |accessdate=28 March 2010}}</ref> As of December 2009, it served 55 stations on {{convert|388|mi}} of track (excluding shared miles) throughout Southern California.<ref name=MetrolinkFact2009 /> Average weekday ridership for the fourth quarter of 2009 was 38,400. Ridership increases almost every year; in July 2008 ridership saw a record 16% increase over the previous year.<ref name=APTAQ42009 /><ref name=LATimesRecord>{{cite news |title=Metrolink sets ridership record, candidates don't talk traffic and sales tax: Ramping up, August 18 |last=Hymon |first=Steve |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=August 2008 |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/bottleneck/2008/08/take-the-olympi.html }}</ref> For 2010, Metrolink was allotted an operating budget of $168.1 million.<ref name=MetrolinkFact2009 /> It is headquartered in the [[MCI Center (Los Angeles)|MCI Center]] in Los Angeles.<ref name=HQ>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinktrains.com/contact/ |title=Contact Us |publisher=Metrolink |accessdate=5 April 2010}}</ref>

==Governance==
The SCRRA is a [[joint powers authority]] governed by five county-level agencies: the [[Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority]], the [[Orange County Transportation Authority]], the [[Riverside County Transportation Commission]], the [[San Bernardino Associated Governments]], and the [[Ventura County Transportation Commission]].<ref name=MetrolinkAbout/> [[Ex officio member|Ex officio]] members include the [[Southern California Association of Governments]], the [[San Diego Association of Governments]], and the state of [[California]].<ref name=MetrolinkFact2009/>

==History==
Beginning in 1990, the member agencies of the SCRRA acquired track and other property from several freight operators: 175 miles of track, maintenance yards, and stations were purchased from [[Southern Pacific]] for $450 million and the rights to use Los Angeles Union Station were purchased from [[Union Pacific]] for $17 million.<ref name=SoCalBusiness>{{cite news |title=LACTC to acquire Union Pacific property and trackage rights for planned five-county commuter rail system. (Los Angeles County Transportation Commission) |newspaper=Southern California Business |date=1 September 1991 |accessdate=28 March 2010 |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-11377072/lactc-acquire-union-pacific.html }}</ref><ref name=RailwayAge>{{cite news |title=California gets it together. (rail systems) |last=Middleton |first=William D. |newspaper=RailwayAge |date=1 November 1992 |accessdate=28 March 2010 |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-12907311/california-gets-together-rail.html }}</ref> The SCRRA was formally founded in 1991.<ref name=MetrolinkAbout>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinktrains.com/about/ |title=About Metrolink |publisher=Metrolink |accessdate=26 March 2010}}</ref>

When Metrolink service began on October 26, 1992, it only operated on three lines: the Ventura, Santa Clarita, and San Bernardino Lines (the Santa Clarita Line later became the Antelope Valley Line).<ref name=FreeLibraryOpening>{{cite web |title=Metrolink Train Service Begins Monday, Oct. 26 |date=22 October 1992 |accessdate=2 April 2010 |publisher=The Free Library |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/METROLINK+TRAIN+SERVICE+BEGINS+MONDAY,+OCT.+26-a012686400}}</ref> In 1993 and 1994, service was expanded to include the Riverside and Orange County Lines, respectively. The Inland Empire-Orange County Line opened in 1995, becoming the first suburb to suburb commuter rail line in the country. The system realized its current form in 2002 with the addition of the 91 Line.<ref name=MetrolinkMilestones>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinktrains.com/about/?id=5 |title=Metrolink Milestones |publisher=Metrolink |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref>

Since July 2005, Metrolink has been operated under contract by [[Veolia Transport]]. After the expiration of the current contract in June, 2010, [[Amtrak]] will resume operation of Metrolink trains, as was the case from 1992 to July 2005.<ref name=MetrolinkMattersMarchApril2010>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinktrains.com/includes/metrolink_matters/MetrolinkMattersMarchAprilWEB.pdf |title=Metrolink Matters |date=March/April 2010 |publisher=Metrolink |accessdate=25 March 2010}}</ref> In the fall of 2009, inward-facing video cameras were installed in locomotives in order to monitor engineers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Metrolink adds video cameras to locomotives |first=Phil |last=Willon |newspaper=Los Angeles Times |date=6 October 2009 |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/06/local/me-metrolink-cameras6}}</ref> Crash energy management cars are being prepared for service in the fleet; they are designed to lessen the toll on passengers in the case of an accident<ref name=CamarilloAcorn>{{cite news |title=Metrolink receives passenger cars specially designed to absorb a crash  |first=Joann |last=Groff |newspaper=Camarillo Acorn |date=12 March 2010 |accessdate=2 April 2010 |url=http://www.thecamarilloacorn.com/news/2010-03-12/Community/Metrolink_receives_passenger_cars_specially_design.html}}</ref> As part of the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act]], over $200 million has been allotted to the SCRRA in order to implement [[positive train control]], a crash-avoidance system.<ref name=Recovery>{{cite web |url=http://www.recovery.org/projectdetails.aspx?pid=ANT:10922757&gloc=San%20Bernardino%20[CA]*CNT:06071 |title=Positive Train Control |date=18 August 2009 |publisher=Onvia, Inc. |accessdate=2 April 2010}}</ref>

==Fares and service==
[[Image:Metrolink Train Station.jpg|thumb|left|Metrolink's [[Burbank (Metrolink station)|Burbank]] station]]
Metrolink's fare structure is based on a flat fee for boarding the train and an additional cost for distance; fares are calculated in 25-cent increments between stations. Prior to July 2004, Metrolink fares were based on price zones radiating outward from Union Station, but a restructuring converted fare calculation to the current system. Fare increases normally occur annually in July to coincide with increased fuel and labor expenses and have generally averaged between 3.5% and 5% per year (although the restructuring caused a larger jump in rates).<ref name=Fares2008>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinktrains.com/news/?id=2321 |title=Metrolink Board approves increase to systemwide and Group Travel Program fares |date=25 April 2008 |publisher=Metrolink |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref> The [[oil price increases since 2003]] are partly to blame for consistently increasing fares as Metrolink trains are powered by [[diesel fuel]].<ref name=FuelCost>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinktrains.com/news/?id=403 |title=EZ transit pass program |publisher=Metrolink |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref>

Metrolink riders can ride most buses in Los Angeles and Orange County, as well as the Metro Rail, free with their valid ticket or pass, and monthly pass holders in Orange and Ventura Counties can use Amtrak Pacific Surfliner and Thruway Coach services through the Rail 2 Rail program.<ref name=EZTransit>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinktrains.com/fares/?id=6 |title=Metrolink Considering Raising Fares Due to Higher Fuel Costs |publisher=Metrolink |date=26 April 2005|accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref>

The rail system experiences its peak ridership during weekday mornings and afternoons.<ref name=FreeCarl>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/AS+FUEL+PRICES+INCREASE,+METROLINK+RIDERSHIP+SOARS.-a083961853 |title=As Fuel Prices Increase, Metrolink Ridership Soars |work=Daily News |publisher=The Free Library|last=Schiermeyer |first=Carl |date=1996 |accessdate=2 April 2010}}</ref> To reflect the demand of its mostly-commuter ridership base, most Metrolink trains operate in the morning between 5 a.m. and 9 a.m. and in the afternoon between 3 p.m. and 9 p.m. Even lines with high ridership (such as the San Bernardino line) operate very few trains outside of the commuter rush hour schedule.<ref name=Schedules /> Metrolink has been willing to add additional trains when funding becomes available, as was the case in [[Orange County, California|Orange County]], when the county decided to subsidize more service.<ref name=LATimesOC>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-07-14/local/me-24009_1_orange-county |title=Metrolink Adds 2 More Trains Per Day for Orange County |last=Berkman |first=Leslie |date=14 July 1995 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref>

==Rail lines==
As a commuter rail line, Metrolink serves mainly to connect Los Angeles to its adjacent suburbs and provide increased accessibility to employment and activity centers.<ref name=MetrolinkAbout /> The system offers travel to a diverse list of destinations, including [[Downtown Los Angeles]], [[Bob Hope Airport]], [[California State University, Los Angeles]], [[Angel Stadium of Anaheim|Angel Stadium]], and the San Clemente Pier.<ref name=Stations>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinktrains.com/stations/ |title=Stations |publisher=Metrolink |accessdate=3 April 2010}}</ref> Special service has also been extended to the [[Fairplex|Pomona Fairplex]],<ref name=PomonaFairplex>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinktrains.com/news/?id=237 |title=Metrolink to Make Special Stops at Fair |publisher=Metrolink |accessdate=3 April 2010}}</ref> the [[Ventura, California#Points of interest|Ventura Fairgrounds]],<ref name=VenturaFairgrounds>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinktrains.com/news/?id=212 |title=Metrolink to Again Offer Service to Ventura County Fair |publisher=Metrolink |accessdate=3 April 2010}}</ref> and the [[Auto Club Speedway]]<ref name=VenturaFairgrounds>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrolinktrains.com/spevents/?id=31 |title=Take Metrolink to the Auto Club Speedway for NASCAR Action! |publisher=Metrolink |accessdate=3 April 2010}}</ref> for certain events.
