==Maintenance facilities==
[[Image:Inside-metrolink.JPG|thumb|The upper level of a Metrolink passenger car]]
===Central Maintenance Facility===
Metrolink's Central Maintenance Facility (CMF) is located on the east bank of the [[Los Angeles River]] near the intersection of the 5 and 110 Freeways, just south of the location of the former Southern Pacific Taylor Yard.<ref name=RiverProject>{{cite web |url=http://www.theriverproject.org/tayloryard/history.html |title=Taylor Yard History |work=The River Project |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref> The facility is operated by Metrolink's equipment maintenance contractor, Bombardier Transportation.<ref name=Bombardier>{{cite web |url=http://www.bombardier.com/en/transportation/about-transportation/worldwide-presence?docID=0901260d8000ede1# |title=Bombardier Transportation in the USA |publisher=Bombardier |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref>

===Camp Pendleton Maintenance Facility===
Metrolink's [[Camp Pendleton]] Facility is located between San Clemente Pier Station and Oceanside Station at the southwest end of Camp Pendleton. This yard is owned by the northern San Diego county [[North County Transit District]] and also services [[Coaster (San Diego)|Coaster]] trains.<ref name=Bombardier />

==Expansion==
Metrolink has grown in popularity in parallel with rising gas prices and the increasing cost of driving. In addition to higher ridership, station parking capacity has also been strained.<ref>{{cite web|last=Reyes |first=David |title=Metrolink growth strains station parking capacity |newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |date= July 5, 2008 |url= http://www.latimes.com/news/local/orange/la-me-stations5-2008jul05,0,5218936.story |accessdate=2008-07-07 }}</ref>

In 2005, the [[Orange County Transportation Authority]] approved a plan to increase frequencies to 76 trains daily on the Orange County and Inland Empire-Orange County Lines by 2009,<ref name=OCRDouble>{{cite news |title=Metrolink daily O.C. service to nearly double |last=Radcliffe |first=Jim |newspaper=Orange County Register |date=14 November 2005 |url=http://www.ocregister.com/articles/service-30056-county-metrolink.html }}</ref> and funding for increased Metrolink service was included in the renewal of the Measure M sales tax for transportation approved by voters in November 2006.<ref name=OCTAM2>{{cite web |url=http://www.octa.net/M2Home.aspx?entryid=332 |title=Measure M2 |publisher=Orange County Transportation Authority |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref> However, in 2010, to save money in the face of funding cuts, the Metrolink board voted to reduce mid-day service on the Inland Empire<U+2013>Orange County Line, as well as weekend service on both the Orange County and Inland Empire<U+2013>Orange County lines.<ref name=LATimesWeekendCuts>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2010/01/metrolink-cuts-some-weekend-service-but-fares-stay-put-for-now.html |title=Metrolink cuts some weekend trains, but fares stay put |last=Connell |first=Rich |date=8 January 2010 |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=26 March 2010}}</ref>

Future plans also call for line expansions extending Metrolink's service area. The proposed [[91 Line]] extension, known officially as the [[Perris Valley Line]], will link [[Riverside, California|Riverside]] and [[Perris, California|Perris]] by 2012.<ref name=Perris>{{cite web |url=http://www.perrisvalleyline.info/schedule.asp |title=Project Schedule |publisher=Riverside County Transportation Commission |accessdate=25 March 2010}}</ref>

[[Image:Metrolink trains outside Union Station.jpg|left|thumb|Metrolink trains approaching and leaving Union Station during the evening rush hour]]A proposed station in [[Yorba Linda, California|Yorba Linda]] was canceled in 2005 due to local opposition. Instead, a [[Placentia, California|Placentia]] Metrolink station which will serve the 91 Line's north Orange County passengers is currently in its final design phase. Construction on the Placentia station will begin in 2012 or 2013; it will be the only station on the 91 Line not shared by another Metrolink line.<ref name=Placentia>{{cite web |url=http://www.octa.net/pdf/Placentia_MetrolinkFactsheet.pdf |title=Placentia Metrolink Station |date=28 January 2009 |publisher=Orange County Transportation Authority |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref>

The Redlands Corridor, a {{convert|9|mi|km|sing=on}} eastward extension linking [[San Bernardino, California|San Bernardino]] with [[Redlands, California|Redlands]] and [[Mentone, California|Mentone]],  is planned by the [[San Bernardino Associated Governments]]. The association is considering whether to extend [[commuter rail]] along the corridor or to install either [[bus rapid transit]] or [[light rail]] lines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sanbag.ca.gov/projects/redlands-transit.html |title=Passenger Rail Extension to Redlands |publisher=San Bernardino Associated Governments |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref>

The [[Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] has proposed adding commuter rail service along the [[Harbor Subdivision (BNSF)|Harbor Subdivision]] corridor, so as to provide service to [[Inglewood, California|Inglewood]], [[Los Angeles International Airport]], the [[South Bay, Los Angeles|South Bay]], the [[Port of Los Angeles]], and/or the [[Port of Long Beach]]. A decision whether to employ commuter rail, light rail, or bus rapid transit in this corridor has not yet been reached.<ref name=MTAHarbor>{{cite web |url=http://www.metro.net/projects_studies/harbor_subdivision/images/AA_study/03-Alternatives.pdf |title=Metro Harbor Subdivision Transit Corridor Alternatives Analysis Report <U+2013> Final |date=November 2009 |work=Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority |accessdate=25 March 2010}}</ref>

In 2008, lobbyists pushed for a rail line to [[Temecula, California|Temecula]] in southwestern Riverside County via the 91 Line's [[Riverside-La Sierra (Metrolink station)|La Sierra station]].<ref name=RCTCFeasability>{{cite web |url=http://www.rctc.org/downloads/railfeasibilitystudy_2008.pdf |title=I-15 Commuter Rail Feasibility Study |date=29 June 2007 |publisher=Wilbur Smith Associates |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref> While this proposed line could follow the route of an abandoned freight line, it would require significant money as freight service ceased almost 30 years ago. Despite this, the Riverside County Transportation Commission's 2008 Commuter Rail Feasibility Study still lists this route as one possibility being considered.<ref name=RCTCStudy>{{cite web |url=http://www.rctc.org/2008commuterrailstudy.asp |title=2008 Commuter Rail Feasibility Study |date=2008 |publisher=Riverside County Transportation Commission |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref>

The cities of the [[Coachella Valley]] ([[Palm Springs, California|Palm Springs]], [[Cathedral City, California|Cathedral City]], [[Palm Desert, California|Palm Desert]], and [[Indio, California|Indio]]) have requested commuter rail service from Los Angeles and Orange County, but the Union Pacific Railroad opposes further passenger service on its tracks.<ref name=CVAG>{{cite web |url=http://rctc.geoclients.com/coachellavalleyrailservice.asp |title=Coachella Valley Rail Service |publisher=Riverside County Transportation Commission |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref> Nonetheless, as recently as 1999, the [[Coachella Valley Association of Governments]] was investigating the possibility of two daily round trips via the 91 Line from Los Angeles's [[Union Station (Los Angeles)|Union Station]] through Fullerton and Riverside to stations in Palm Springs and Indio (with a possible stop near [[Palm Desert, California|Palm Desert]]),<ref name=RCTCCoachella>{{cite web |url=http://www.rctc.org/downloads/1999%20Coachella%20Valley%20Rail%20Study.pdf |title=Coachella Valley Passenger Rail Feasibility Study |date=February 1999 |publisher=Schiermeyer Consulting Services |accessdate=27 March 2010}}</ref> possibly through a partnership with [[Amtrak]]. What effect these might have on the 91 Line's Perris Valley extension (or vice versa) is not discussed. This extension would likewise require significant money for infrastructure improvements: at least $500 million, according to the California State Rail Plan of 2005.<ref name=CVAG/>

== Rolling stock ==
[[Image:Metrolink_F59PHI_885.jpg|thumb|Late afternoon train passing through [[Lake Forest, California]]]]
The Metrolink fleet consists of 52 locomotives and 171 [[Bombardier BiLevel Coach]]es with 117 Rotem Bi-level cars on order. As of March 2010, the cab car portion of the fleet consists of 33 Metrolink-owned cab cars and 2 leased from [[Altamont Commuter Express]] (ACE). The trailer portion of the fleet includes 103 Metrolink-owned trailers, 2 leased from ACE,  10 leased from [[Utah Transit Authority]], and 15 leased from [[New Jersey Transit]].<ref name=MetrolinkFact2009/>

